snippet.textDisplay:
I am from a country that has been under lock down for 5 days (hi, i'm bored)
It is for sure important, even though I was against it first, since it is taking away a lot freedom, now I support it, my country has a border to Italy and it's bad.

But! Only after 5 days the rise of domestic violence is visible and the women-protection-centres prepare for the worst, kids with alcoholic or aggressive parents will have a hard time, my aunt has a handicapped child and no break at all. It is so hard on all of them.

We cannot sugarcoat these measures as "oh just watch more tv", for many people it will be really really hard and there needs to be help for them as well.

All the best from quarantined Austria with the most beautiful start of spring ever (outside, greaaaat)

snippet.textDisplay:
If your search for protective measures against coronavirus, you will find the following:
1. HANDS Wash them often
2. ELBOW Cough into it
3. FACE Don't touch it
4. FEET Stay more than 3 feet apart
5. FEEL sick? Stay home


I get the part about washing your hands, but if you are sneezing into your elbow then your elbow is contaminated!
It's nearly impossible to not touch your face; especially if you are going to sneeze into your elbow creating a breeding ground for germs and sneezing into them again touching your face.
It is difficult to stay 3 feet apart especially if you have kids and elderly who needs your care.
And if you are sick there isn't much to do other than staying home and taking measures to coupe with the virus.


Here is a little something you can do in addition to what you are doing to prevent the virus.
Don't just wash your hands and PURELL


Wash your hands till the wrists 3 times
rinse your mouth 3 times
clean your nose 3 times
wash your face 3 times
wash your hands till the elbows 3 times
wipe your hair
wipe your neck
wipe your ears both inside and behind
wash your feet 3 times


If you are sneezing into your elbow, or have touched your face or have been close to others; doing the above should help wash away the germs and might even prevent the spread.


spend time meditating, stretching and exercising for 5 minutes. This will help refresh your mind and raise your spirit while in isolation.


repeat this every day 5 times a day:
- before sunrise
- after mid-day
- after mid-afternoon
- after sunset
- before going to sleep


Doing so will ensure you are clean and raise your spirit all day every day.


if you are taking a piss, do it sitting down on the toilet seat or squatting just as you would while taking a dump; this will prevent it from splashing around the toilet seat or even splashing on to you.
don't just use a tissue to wipe yourself after you are done; clean it with water and then use a tissue to dry yourself. That way you will limit the waste of tissue and still have them when you need them the most.


And it also goes without saying; brush your teeth and shower every day.

snippet.textDisplay: When I isolated in China, the time during Chinese lunar new year holiday, normally it was only 7 days but this year i spent more than one month closely living with my parents, I’ve never been with them more than a decade since I left for study and work. As you said, connecting yourself and the people around, I can’t agree with you more, this’s the best time for me to deeply think how my life style worked and pay more attention to balance life goal and health, even future finance plan for myself and family. Just like meditation period, besides these days I found some changes(almost ignored coz separated living) from my getting-older parents,    Before we often dissatisfied each other. This virus War built us more love-centered and stronger. Another good news I wanna share is when I isolated at home and looked outside of the window, everyday only cleaners working at streets, extremely less cars less noise less gas less pollution, guess what, I saw beautiful birds singing, squirrels playing, stray animals walking...life’s more natural and creatures-diverse.

For anyone stuck at home, here's a free cloth face mask sewing pattern: https://www.instructables.com/id/DIY-Cloth-Face-Mask/


I had some spare fabric laying around, and I made one of these. It was a fun way to pass the time, and now I have a matching mask and hat!


We don't know if we're asymptomatic carriers if we haven't been tested. And a cloth mask is better than nothing, and will leave more masks available for hospitals and nursing homes.
